Wonka World

by: Gizem

This game was made for my level 2 project at The League of Amazing Programmers.
Click here to download and play!

1. Why I Made This Game

I decided to make this game because I thought a candy concept would be fun opposed to a fighting game which we already made this level. The side view of the game seemed to be a cool take on game because then people could see where to go and what was around the character.

2. What I Learned

I learnt that even though my game might work on my computer, it could be different on someone else's. The feedback I got consisted of fixing a bug between the switching of the frames and how some candies were spawning under the floor.

3. Architecture of My Game

My game has a moveable character, candies, platforms, and a timer. Willy Wonka(the character) had to be able to stand on the platform without falling through, whilst collecting the candy objects around. And then the timer had to take into account how many candies were left and continue updating to display a decreasing number.

4. Technical Implementation

An aspect of my game that I am most proud of is the platforms. When I first created the boxes, they were just pictures on a screen so I somehow had to make it so that Willy Wonka couldn't pass through them. The code that I wrote for this worked until a jump feature was added in. After that I spent several weeks trying to figure out how to get pass this problem and at some point we found out that it had to do with the x and y values of my character. When we solved that, I began working on a timer so my game could have a goal.

5. Most Challenging Part

The most challenging part of this project was getting the platforms to work and the jump feature, plus small little bugs that stumped me. I overcame these problems by asking for help from my teachers and parents, and spending some time outside of class on my game.

6. Future Fixes and Updates

If I were to continue working on this game, I would like to create better graphics (maybe something I drew myself), add more components into the game such as a small enemy to distract the player.
